                <!--[BEFORE-ARTICLE]--><span class=3D"marker before-article=
"></span><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D"ref1"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class=
=3D"marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong>=
<span id=3D"ref221054"></span>Mohs hardness</strong>,  rough measure of the=
 resistance of a smooth surface to scratching or abrasion, expressed in ter=
ms of a scale <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-=
term=3D"devised" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/devised" dat=
a-type=3D"EB">devised</a> (1812) by the German mineralogist <span id=3D"ref=
221055"></span>Friedrich Mohs. The Mohs hardness of a <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.britannica.com/science/mineral-chemical-compound" class=3D"md-crosslink "=
 data-show-preview=3D"true">mineral</a> is determined by observing whether =
its surface is scratched by a substance of known or defined <a href=3D"http=
s://www.britannica.com/science/hardness-physics" class=3D"md-crosslink auto=
xref " data-show-preview=3D"true">hardness</a>.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class=
=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span><!--[PREMOD2]--><span class=3D"marker PR=
EMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">To give numerical val=
ues to this physical property, minerals are ranked along the Mohs scale, wh=
ich is composed of 10 minerals that have been given arbitrary hardness valu=
es. The minerals contained in the scale are shown in the <span id=3D"ref622=
"></span>Table; also shown are other materials that approximate the hardnes=
s of some of the minerals. As is indicated by the ranking in the scale, if =
a mineral is scratched by <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/ort=
hoclase" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">orthoclase</a> =
but not by <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/apatite" class=3D"=
md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">apatite</a>, its Mohs hardness is=
 between 5 and 6. In the determination procedure it is necessary to be cert=
ain that a scratch is actually made and not just a =E2=80=9Cchalk=E2=80=9D =
mark that will rub off. If the species being tested is fine-grained, friabl=
e, or pulverulent, the test may only loosen grains without testing individu=
al mineral surfaces; thus, certain textures or <a class=3D"md-dictionary-li=
nk md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"aggregate" href=3D"https://www.mer=
riam-webster.com/dictionary/aggregate" data-type=3D"MW">aggregate</a> forms=
 may hinder or prevent a true hardness determination. For this reason the M=
ohs test, while greatly <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off=
 mw" data-term=3D"facilitating" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dic=
tionary/facilitating" data-type=3D"MW">facilitating</a> the identification =
of minerals in the field, is not suitable for accurately gauging the hardne=
ss of industrial materials such as <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/te=
chnology/steel" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">steel</a=
> or <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/technology/traditional-ceramics"=
 class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">ceramics</a>. (For thes=
e materials a more precise measure is to be found in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/www.britannica.com/science/Vickers-hardness" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-=
show-preview=3D"true">Vickers hardness</a> or <a href=3D"https://www.britan=
nica.com/science/Knoop-hardness" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">Knoop hardness</a>.) </p><div class=3D"js-qf-module qf-module px-=
40 px-sm-20 py-15 mx-auto module-spacing font-14 bg-gray-50 rounded">

