div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D=
"ref1" data-has-spy=3D"true"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD1 =
mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong><span id=3D"ref6192=
56"></span>mineral</strong>,  naturally occurring <a class=3D"md-dictionary=
-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"homogeneous" href=3D"https://ww=
w.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/homogeneous" data-type=3D"MW">homogeneous<=
/a> <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/solid-state-of-matter" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">solid</a> with a definite =
chemical <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=
=3D"composition" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/composi=
tion" data-type=3D"MW">composition</a> and a highly ordered <a href=3D"http=
s://www.britannica.com/science/atom" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-prev=
iew=3D"true">atomic</a> arrangement; it is usually formed by inorganic proc=
esses. There are several thousand known mineral species, about 100 of which=
 <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"const=
itute" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/constitute" data-=
type=3D"MW">constitute</a> the major mineral components of <a href=3D"https=
://www.britannica.com/science/rock-geology" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-sh=
ow-preview=3D"true">rocks</a>; these are the so-called rock-forming mineral=
s.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span></section>





<!--[H2]--><span class=3D"marker h2"></span><div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-=
target"></div><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D"ref80352" data-has-spy=3D"tru=
e"><h2 class=3D"h1">Definition</h2>
<!--[PREMOD2]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class=
=3D"topic-paragraph">A mineral, which by definition must be formed through =
natural processes, is distinct from the <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-d=
ictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"synthetic" href=3D"https://www.merriam-we=
bster.com/dictionary/synthetic" data-type=3D"MW">synthetic</a> equivalents =
produced in the laboratory. Artificial versions of minerals, including <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/emerald-gemstone" class=3D"md-cross=
link " data-show-preview=3D"true">emeralds</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.brit=
annica.com/topic/sapphire-gemstone" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">sapphires</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/diam=
ond-gemstone" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">diamonds</=
a>, and other valuable <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/gemsto=
ne" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">gemstones</a>, are r=
egularly produced in industrial and research facilities and are often nearl=
y identical to their natural counterparts.</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class=3D"m=
arker MOD2 mod-inline"></span>
<!--[PREMOD3]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD3 mod-inline"></span><p class=
=3D"topic-paragraph">By its definition as a <span id=3D"ref619258"></span><=
a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/homogeneity" class=3D"md-cross=
link ">homogeneous </a>solid, a mineral is composed of a single solid subst=
ance of uniform composition that cannot be physically separated into simple=
r <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/chemical-compound" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">chemical compounds</a>. <a class=
=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"Homogeneity" h=
ref=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Homogeneity" data-type=3D=
"MW">Homogeneity</a> is determined relative to the scale on which it is def=
ined. A specimen that appears homogeneous to the unaided eye, for example, =
may reveal several mineral components under a <a href=3D"https://www.britan=
nica.com/technology/microscope" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">microscope</a> or upon exposure to <a href=3D"https://www.britann=
ica.com/science/X-ray-diffraction" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previe=
w=3D"true">X-ray diffraction</a> techniques. Most rocks are composed of sev=
eral different minerals; e.g., <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/scienc=
e/granite" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">granite</a> c=
onsists of <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/feldspar" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">feldspar</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/www.britannica.com/science/quartz" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">quartz</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/mica"=
 class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">mica</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/amphibole" class=3D"md-crosslink " d=
ata-show-preview=3D"true">amphibole</a>. In addition, <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.britannica.com/science/gas-state-of-matter" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-=
show-preview=3D"true">gases</a> and <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/s=
cience/liquid-state-of-matter" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D=
"true">liquids</a> are excluded by a strict interpretation of the above def=
inition of a mineral. <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/ice" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Ice</a>, the solid state o=
f <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/water" class=3D"md-crosslin=
k " data-show-preview=3D"true">water</a> (H<sub>2</sub>O), is considered a =
mineral, but liquid water is not; liquid <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.=
com/science/mercury-chemical-element" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-pre=
view=3D"true">mercury</a>, though sometimes found in mercury <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.britannica.com/science/ore-mining" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref =
" data-show-preview=3D"true">ore</a> deposits, is not classified as a miner=
al either. Such substances that resemble minerals in <a href=3D"https://www=
.britannica.com/science/chemistry" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previe=
w=3D"true">chemistry</a> and occurrence are dubbed mineraloids and are incl=
uded in the general domain of <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science=
/mineralogy" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">mineralogy<=
/a>.</p><!--[MOD3]--><span class=3D"marker MOD3 mod-inline"></span>
