<span>Trigonal (rhombohedral) crystals of quartz.</span><button class=3D"js=
-more-btn d-none btn btn-unstyled font-12 bg-white js-content" aria-label=
=3D"Toggle more/less fact data"><span class=3D"link-blue">(more)</span></bu=
tton></span></div></figcaption></figure></div></div><p class=3D"topic-parag=
raph">Since a mineral has a definite composition, it can be expressed by a =
specific <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/chemical-formula" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">chemical formula<=
/a>. Quartz (silicon dioxide), for instance, is rendered as SiO<sub>2</sub>=
, because the <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/chemical-elemen=
t" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">elements</a> <a href=
=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/silicon" class=3D"md-crosslink " dat=
a-show-preview=3D"true">silicon</a> (Si) and <a href=3D"https://www.britann=
ica.com/science/oxygen" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">=
oxygen</a> (O) are its only <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt=
-off mw" data-term=3D"constituents" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com=
/dictionary/constituents" data-type=3D"MW">constituents</a> and they invari=
ably appear in a 1:2 ratio. The chemical makeup of most minerals is not as =
well defined as that of quartz, which is a pure substance. <a href=3D"https=
://www.britannica.com/science/siderite" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-p=
review=3D"true">Siderite</a>, for example, does not always occur as pure <a=
 href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/iron-chemical-element" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">iron</a> carbonate (FeCO<sub>3</=
sub>); <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/magnesium" class=3D"md=
-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">magnesium</a> (Mg), <a href=3D"http=
s://www.britannica.com/science/manganese" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show=
-preview=3D"true">manganese</a> (Mn), and, to a limited extent, <a href=3D"=
https://www.britannica.com/science/calcium" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-sh=
ow-preview=3D"true">calcium</a> (Ca) may sometimes substitute for the iron.=
 Since the amount of the replacement may vary, the composition of siderite =
is not fixed and ranges between certain limits, although the ratio of the <=
a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/metal-chemistry" class=3D"md-c=
rosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">metal</a> <a href=3D"https://www.brit=
annica.com/science/cation" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"tru=
e">cation</a> to the <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/anion" c=
lass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">anionic</a> group remains=
 fixed at 1:1. Its chemical makeup may be expressed by the general formula =
(Fe, Mn, Mg, Ca)CO<sub>3</sub>, which reflects the variability of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/metal-chemistry" class=3D"md-cross=
link " data-show-preview=3D"true">metal</a> content.</p><!--[MOD4]--><span =
class=3D"marker MOD4 mod-inline"></span>
