unstyled font-12 bg-white js-content" aria-label=3D"Toggle more/less fact d=
ata"><span class=3D"link-blue">(more)</span></button></span></div></figcapt=
ion></figure></div></div><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Minerals display a hi=
ghly ordered internal atomic structure that has a regular geometric form. B=
ecause of this feature, minerals are classified as crystalline solids. Unde=
r favourable conditions, crystalline materials may express their ordered in=
ternal framework by a well-developed external form, often referred to as <a=
 href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/crystal" class=3D"md-crosslink =
" data-show-preview=3D"true">crystal</a> form or <a class=3D"md-dictionary-=
link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"morphology" href=3D"https://www.=
merriam-webster.com/dictionary/morphology" data-type=3D"MW">morphology</a>.=
 Solids that exhibit no such ordered internal arrangement are termed <a cla=
ss=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"amorphous" h=
ref=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/amorphous" data-type=3D"M=
W">amorphous</a>. Many amorphous natural solids, such as <a href=3D"https:/=
/www.britannica.com/technology/glass" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-pre=
view=3D"true">glass</a>, are categorized as mineraloids.</p><a class=3D"lin=
