l=3D"Toggle more/less fact data"><span class=3D"link-blue">(more)</span></b=
utton></span></div></figcaption></figure></div></div><p class=3D"topic-para=
graph">While minerals are classified in a logical manner according to their=
 major <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/anion" class=3D"md-cro=
sslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">anionic</a> (negatively charged) chemic=
al <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"con=
stituents" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/constituents" data=
-type=3D"EB">constituents</a> into groups such as <a href=3D"https://www.br=
itannica.com/science/oxide" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"tr=
ue">oxides</a>, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/silicate-mine=
ral" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">silicates</a>, and =
<a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/nitrate" class=3D"md-crosslin=
k " data-show-preview=3D"true">nitrates</a>, they are named in a far less s=
cientific or consistent way. Names may be assigned to reflect a physical or=
 chemical property, such as colour, or they may be derived from various sub=
jects deemed appropriate, such as, for example, a locality, public figure, =
or mineralogist. Some examples of mineral names and their derivations follo=
w: <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/albite" class=3D"md-crossl=
ink " data-show-preview=3D"true">albite</a> (NaAlSi<sub>3</sub>O<sub>8</sub=
>) is from the <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/Latin" class=3D"=
md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Latin</a> word (<em>albus</em>) f=
or =E2=80=9Cwhite=E2=80=9D in reference to its colour; <a href=3D"https://w=
ww.britannica.com/science/goethite" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-s=
how-preview=3D"true">goethite</a> (FeO =E2=88=99 OH) is in honour of <a hre=
f=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Johann-Wolfgang-von-Goethe" class=
=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Johann Wolfgang von Goethe</a=
>, the German poet; <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/manganite=
" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">manganite</a> (MnO =E2=
=88=99 OH) reflects the mineral=E2=80=99s composition; franklinite (ZnFe<su=
b>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub>) is named after Franklin, <a href=3D"https://www.bri=
tannica.com/place/New-Jersey" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-pr=
eview=3D"true">New Jersey</a>, U.S., the site of its occurrence as the domi=
nant ore mineral for <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/zinc" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">zinc</a> (Zn); and <a href=
=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/sillimanite" class=3D"md-crosslink "=
 data-show-preview=3D"true">sillimanite</a> (Al<sub>2</sub>SiO<sub>4</sub>)=
 is in honour of the American chemist <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com=
/biography/Benjamin-Silliman-American-chemist-1816-1885" class=3D"md-crossl=
ink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Benjamin Silliman</a>. Since 1960 the <a c=
lass=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"Commission=
" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/Commission" data-type=3D"EB=
">Commission</a> on New Minerals and Mineral Names of the International Min=
eralogical Association has reviewed descriptions of new minerals and propos=
als for new mineral names and has attempted to remove inconsistencies. Any =
new mineral name must be approved by this committee, and the type material =
is usually stored in a <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/museum-c=
ultural-institution" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">mus=
eum</a> or <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/topic/university" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">university</a> collection.</p><d=
